 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1939 and 1945, some 80,000 Finnish children were sent to Sweden, Denmark, and elsewhere, ostensibly to protect them from danger while their nation’s soldiers fought superior Soviet and German forces. This was the largest of all of World War II children’s transports, and although acknowledged today as “a great social-historical mistake,” it has received surprisingly little attention. This is the first English-language account of Finland’s war children and their experiences, told through the survivors’ own words. Supported by an extensive introduction, a bibliography of secondary sources, and over two dozen photographs, this book testifies to the often-lifelong traumas endured by youthful survivors of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChildrenzFinlandvBiography. 0aChildrenzSwedenvBiography. 0aFinnszSwedenvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Finnish. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzFinland. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzSweden. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xEvacuation of civilianszFinland. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  a1939.  a1945.  aaccount of finlands war childrens experiences.  abibliography of secondary sources.  adenmark.  aextensive introduction.  afinland.  afinnish children.  agreat social historical mistake.  ahistorical nonfiction.  alargest wwii children transport.  alifelong traumas.  anarrative account of finlands war children.  aover two dozen photographs.  asent away to protect them.  asoldiers fought superior axis powers.  asoviet and german forces.  asweden.  awwii.  ayouthful survivors of war.1 aEskola, Emmi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankkila, Juh